Salmonella myonecrosis in a patient with diabetes mellitus.
 Bacterial myonecrosis is a medical and surgical emergency and prompt surgical intervention is critically important.
 A variety of microorganisms have been isolated from patients with necrotizing soft-tissue infections.
 These infections are frequently polymicrobial in etiology, but occasionally a single microorganism is isolated.
 This report describes a case of crepitant myonecrosis from infection with Salmonella serogroup B.
